         <abstract>
            <p>
               <bold>Abstract</bold>Nine Dolby theatrical “trailers” were made from the mid-1990s to 2003 specifically to visualize and promote the audio capabilities of digital sound. Drawing on Bachelard's<italic>The Poetics of Space</italic>and Chion's<italic>Audio-Vision</italic>, this essay explores the trailers' sound-driven imagery and suggests its implications for contemporary “mainstream” narrative cinema.</p>
